/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/promising-findings.md:439:## 10. Yang-Mills Mass Gap — β < 1/6 Threshold (8× State of the Art) [PROOF GAP FOUND]
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/promising-findings.md:443:**The result:** The β < 1/6 mass gap threshold is numerically correct but the proof has an irreparable gap. The B² formula step (HessS(v,v) = (β/2N)Σ|B□(Q,v)|²) is NOT an identity at generic Q — it's exact only at flat connections. Follow-up validation found λ_max(H_actual) > λ_max(H_formula) for one-hot perturbations at d≥3. The excess is small (≤ 2.6% at d=2, ≤ 0.5% at d=4), so the conclusion is approximately correct.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/promising-findings.md:462:**Honest limits:** β < 1/6 is NOT rigorously proved as stated. A direct proof via the analytical Hessian formula (bypassing B²) could give β < 1/3 or better, but hasn't been attempted. All results remain in the strongly-confined regime, far from the continuum limit needed for the Millennium Prize.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/promising-findings.md:470:### 20. Lattice Yang-Mills Mass Gap: β < 1/6 via Hessian Sharpness [PROOF GAP]
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/promising-findings.md:474:**The proof (with gap):** SZZ's Bakry-Emery condition gives mass gap for β < 1/(48·H_norm). SZZ bounds H_norm ≤ 1 (giving β < 1/48). The triangle inequality improvement gives λ_max(M(Q)) ≤ 8(d-1) = 24, hence H_norm ≤ 24/48 = 1/8, hence β < 1/6. However, the step identifying HessS with (β/2N)M is NOT an identity — it's exact only at flat connections (Q=I). At generic Q, λ_max(H_actual) can exceed λ_max(H_formula) by up to 2.6% (d=2) or 0.5% (d=4). The B² formula route is definitively broken.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/home-base/current_hunts/big-thinkers/research-systems/codex-philosopher-atlas/promising-findings.md:476:**What survives:** The triangle inequality bound on M(Q) itself is correct. The conclusion (β < 1/6 has a mass gap) is numerically well-supported. A proof bypassing the B² formula via the analytical Hessian is viable but unattempted.
